We love us some @simonebiles She’s a wonderful role model for children. After reading a children’s book about her life, my kids are inspired, and they start doing cartwheels on the sofa. “Flying High” is a biographical book about Simon Biles. It’s written by Michelle Meadows and illustrated by @artsyebby. 

The book is wonderful! The rhyming pattern makes it fun to read. You get a small glimpse into Simone's backstory and fittingly, the last line of the book is “Simone captures her dream, and America’s heart”.

Be encouraged @simonbiles We continue to be inspired by your life. The greatest achievers also need a break #simonbiles #davechappelle #naomiosaka #michaeljordanbaseball

🎥 @dual.vizion.photos 

#puzzlehuddle

Thanks @adrianadiaz and @debraalfarone for capturing our family business story.  The path to create @puzzlehuddle started with a pair of scissors, foam board, and a few glossy 8 x 10 prints. Something in my heart told me I needed a plan to partner with a manufacturer, because I wanted a puzzle for every kid in my network. At the time I was a father of 3 with a full-time job, and I couldn't sit around cutting homemade puzzles with a pair of scissors all day.

In hindsight, I had to start this journey because I was losing a lot of sleep thinking about how to share a diversity focused puzzle with as many families as possible.

We are moving beyond the home-based business category. The decision to lease an external space was filled with anxiousness and courage. I believe in our mission, products, strategy and community. Intermittently, I wonder if the success we’ve had is a mirage and I get concerned about overextending. 

In 2020, our business experienced increased sales based on school closures, media attention on the Black Lives Matter Movement, and getting listed among Oprah’s Favorite Things. These events created new opportunities for our company. It's unlikely that this sequence of macro events will happen in the same way again.

Operating from home has been comparatively safe financially and emotionally. There are other options to grow an ecommerce company that don't require a lease, including, partnering with an ecommerce shipping company.

Working away from home while parenting young children will require a new family logistics plan. I have enjoyed being present with my children at home and quickly transitioning from family experiences to business requirements.

We can't reach all of the families we want to support by shipping from our basement forever. With conviction we are moving into the next phase of business and I love it! Thanks for all your support.

Side note: We’ve been very fortunate to work with a crew of awesome staff members at @ups and @uspostalservice. Our local drivers are fantastic! 

📸 @dual.vizion.photos #puzzlehuddle

node.text:
Oct, 2019 -  I decided to record myself reading with my children. A few of the reasons included: 

- The activity helped me create a habit around reading with my children during the day when I have more energy and patience (vs. bedtime reading).

- I wanted to capture my children's voices, grammar, pronunciation, etc...before they grow out of this phase of their development. 

- I hoped to develop their confidence and composure for public speaking and sharing with an audience.

- It’s important to put robust traditions around things that are important. I want learning and education to take up a lot of space in our lives.

I hesitated to start because I wasn't sure if I could keep it up, but I love capturing this time with them, and that makes the habit easier to maintain. A year and a half later we have more polished production capabilities with @dual.vizion.photos, but I started with leaning my phone against a pillow. 

#puzzlehuddle #fatherdaughter #fatherhood #dadlife #raisingreaders #childrensbooks

node.text:
Wife-tastic gave me an incredible framed “warehouse-warming” gift to celebrate moving @PuzzleHuddle out of our kitchen, living room, and dining room; into a formal business location a few months ago. 

Getting featured on lists and in publications can certainly help a business grow, but we don't have a PR team and it's not something we focus on. I’m often asked “how did you get @oprah and her team’s attention?” I truly have no idea. My best guess is the team saw one of our social media posts; but that’s just a theory I made up with no additional information. 

We shipped the tidal wave of Oprah’s Favorite Things orders from our basement. Along the way, our shipping team generally stayed in our house until midnight, we needed help but we were concerned about people and COVID entering the house, we were taking up too many parking spaces in our residential neighborhood, at times there would be up to three UPS trucks parked in front, and we piled an an unconscionable number of discarded boxes in the alley for recycling pick-up…..it was amazing and my entrepreneurial heart was full of joy!

It's an honor to ship our products to each and every one of you. Thanks so much for your support along the way.

📸 @dual.vizion.photos 

#puzzlehuddle 
#smallbusiness

Chris Benard (@flyylikechrisb) is a two-time Olympian and represented the United States in the Men’s Triple Jump. His favorite childhood books include the Harry Potter series. The books provided his first introduction to an underdog story and they made him feel like anything was possible. Chris’s  favorite toys were anything with wheels: bikes, skateboards, skates, and scooters. The toys gave him a sense of independence.

A childhood experience that helped shape Chris’ path was watching his father earn a bachelors and masters degrees while working full-time in the Marines. He went straight from work to class; after getting home he helped Chris and his sister with their homework. Next, he needed to do his own homework. Watching that instilled a work ethic that shaped his future.

#puzzlehuddle
#triplejump
#teamusa

node.text:
Nadia Chika Eke (@nadeekz) represented Ghana at the Tokyo Olympics in the Women’s Triple Jump. Although she pursued athletics growing up, she was also given the freedom to express herself through art and dance, which became vessels for her  to connect with others. 

Her grandmother always took care of children who didn't have much, taught them a trade, and paid for their education. Although her life and privilege were different, her grandmother made sure she understood that they were no different. She was required to do the same things they did, like “street hawking”; which in her case meant selling bread on the streets. 

In order to maintain her mental health under pressure, she treats herself to good food. Nadia believes that she deserves the best and rewards herself when things go well, and when they don't go well. Nadia describes herself as a talker, so she gains fresh perspectives from connecting with new people and collecting their stories. 

At an early  age, a few things she learned that contributed to her success were; the value of hard work, how to hustle, and how to connect with others in order to have influence. 

#puzzlehuddle
#teamghana
#tokyo2021 
#triplejump
